examples: Bu korroko duruk bokenh Adjumarlarl dja Omwarl benemwam karrikadbeh kukku benehboyawani.

examples: Nawu korroko bininj birriyuhyungki birrimulewarreni bu bedda kunwok bedberre kore birriwokdi. Yika manbu kunwok mankang kuberrkbeh dja yika kore kurrulabeh. Wanjh bolkkime bininj birriwern kabirribebbehwokdi manbu kunwok bedberre. Yiman Amurdak dja Wardadjbak makka kuberrkbeh birriwokdi. Dja manbu Yibadjdja dja Marrkku makka wanjh kumekke ngalengman kore kabirrihni bolkkime bininj manbu kunwok kumekke kabirridjalwokdi.
(Jill Nganjmirra)

In the old days, our ancestors all spoke to each other in their own languages. Some languages came from inland areas, and others from saltwater areas. Still today, people each talk their own languages. Amurdak and Wardadjbak for example were spoken in inland areas. Iwaidja and Marrku are still spoken where the speakers of those languages live.
Nawu manimunak wirlarrk djang kahdjangdi kore kaddum kuwardde Arrkuluk.
(Andrew Manakgu, Injalak Arts painting documentation)

translation: 1. place name in the Gunbalanya township 2. place name in Birrirddak Creek region

examples: Awurd, mayh namekke ngan­kodjborledke Kawk Kabim Djang
(Nabarlek Band song (Terrah Guymala))
Yika mak ngarriyime "awurd" bu nangale nawu kare djarre wanjh ngarrikongibun, dja mak bininj nawu karrowen, wanjh ngarriyime "awurd warre mankang mandengeyi".
(Jill Nganjmirra )
So dear to me is that bird, its call reminds me of the sacred night heron dreaming.

We might say “fv: Awurd” (“Oh that dear man/woman”) if someone goes far away and we feel sorry for them, or for example if someone dies we might say "Awurd (oh that poor man/woman) it’s a terrible thing, they had a car crash".
translation: goodness me, 'oh how dear it is'

examples: Baddumang ngarrikebnarren.

Warlirr kundung karrirung, kunekke kadberre karrirung, dja baddumang kabirrikarrme, baddumang kabirrikarrme kune kayime kakolhdebebme, kakolhdebebme, soon kabirrikarrme, glass, mirror, soon kabirrikarrme kadberre yiman muddikang rerri. Bokenh kabenekarrme, glass baddumang kukak kabirribebme.

When the sun is hot, when we get really hot, then they have pieces of glass and when plants start sending out new growth [just before rain comes] then they [spirit beings] have pieces of glass and they take us away in something like a motor vehicle. They are in pairs with their pieces of glass and they appear at night.

It belonged (the dreaming) to that old Badmardi clansman Nangukwirridj, yeah

She split it all [the pandanus leaves] into strips, then put them in the sun to dry. They lay there in the sun and all dried out.
Yirrmeng rowk wanjh mey daweng, dayohdayoy dayonginj rowk darlehminj.
Burarr karrinan kakukdayo kore kunwardde kukorlh kore manwodj kahwodjyo kundulk.

She split it all [the pandanus leaves] into strips, then put them in the sun to dry. They lay there in the sun and all dried out.

Birridedjbuni birrinjamduhkeyi birribebkeyi mannjam kundurddu kudiw kunbalem dja njalehnjale rowk kore kunj kunjam.
(Andrew Manakgu, Injalak Arts painting documentation )
They would cut open the kangaroo, make an opening in its belly and pull out the stomach, heart, liver, fat and everything else inside.
Ngaleng nalkbom, nalkbom dja dedjdjingmey wayihwayini.
(Nganjmirra, Nawakadj, ‘Kunwinjku Spirit’, Melbourne University Press, 1997, p. 132)
She cried and cried, then began to sing.
Ngaldedjdjumbung ngalkka.
That short woman.
Banikkin dedjlarrk.
(Jill Nganjmirra)

(Jill Nganjmirra)
Dedjlarrkminj nawu bakki.
(Jill Nganjmirra)
A cup without a bottom, a cup with a big hole in the bottom of it.
"Give me some money." "I don't have any money, the bag is empty."

Kabirridirri budbol wanjh nakudji nawu kadedjmelme manbu budbol wanjh kadolkayhwe djarreh kare.

Grandpa let me come in, I'm getting rained on and I'm freezing and shivering.
Manih delek ngukmak, kakukbarme duninj.
This white clay is 'good shit' (of the rainbow serpent), it really is very bright.

examples: Kadjalbodelengkurrme kabongerdkendi wanjh.
(Nadjamerrek, Lofty Bardayal & Garde, Murray (ed.), ‘A Kundedjnjenghmi Wordlist of Eco-zone Terminology’, Northern Land Council Caring for Country Unit, 2007)
Dalukdeleng beneburrinj?
Wanjh ngadman deleng bu ngarrinahnarren / Minj nangale ngankongibun bu konda kamre, ahwurd, ahwurd.
(Wildflower Band, ’Maburrinj (The lonely place called Maburrinj)’, from the Album ‘Manginburru Bininj’, Skinnyfish Music, 2009)
The water goes in until it is full.
Was it only the two women [and not men] who were fighting?
We look after ourselves / No one feels sorry for us, no one is staying here, we are sad, we are sad.
Bu kabbal karrire wanjh kunkih karrikihmelme wanjh kandelkke kunkih.
(Andrew Manakgu, Injalak Arts painting documentation )
When we go onto the floodplain and step in the mud, the mud splashes us.
Kanwohdenghke.
Bu yiman wurdwurdbubuyika mak kabirridurren, wanjh karrbendenghke o karrbenmarneyime “Yuwn ngurrimarneyidngalkerren”.
(Quoted in Etherington, Steve, ‘Learning to be Kunwinjku: Kunwinjku people discuss their pedagogy’, PhD Thesis, Charles Darwin University, 2006)
You're delaying me (i.e. I want to go).
If other kids start arguing with them, we stop them, or we tell them “Don’t go looking for trouble for yourself.”

Karridjalkukdenghme munguyh.

We're stalled, we're not moving forward (no-one is co-operating or taking decisive action).
Yiderrehkemen darnki kodbarre.
Move it away (and put it) close to the house.
Yiderrehmen!
Yimderrehmen!
Karridubberrong yiman bolkkime karridi, karridubbedoy wanjh. Dja bu bewh wurd karribalderrehme.
(Quoted in Etherington, Steve, ‘Learning to be Kunwinjku: Kunwinjku people discuss their pedagogy’, PhD Thesis, Charles Darwin University, 2006)

Yuwn ngurriwernhre kunrayek kore Balanda. Bokenh ngurrirlobmen. Ngad kadberre mak kunwok ngurrikarrmen rerrih, yuwn ngurriwe, la ngurrire kore kunkukbele, burrkyak. Marndi bewh ngurrihderrehme djarreh ngurrikarrebarlanhmang manbu ngad kadberre.
(Quoted in Etherington, Steve, ‘Learning to be Kunwinjku: Kunwinjku people discuss their pedagogy’, PhD Thesis, Charles Darwin University, 2006)
Bindimarneyimeng, “Ngurriderrehmen ngudda ngurrikukbele ngurriderrehmen wardi bu ngadman bininjwi.”
(Quoted in Etherington, Steve, ‘Learning to be Kunwinjku: Kunwinjku people discuss their pedagogy’, PhD Thesis, Charles Darwin University, 2006)
Move away a bit.
Come closer.
We don’t know which way to go at present, as we are now, we're stuck. We need to make progress.

Don’t dedicate yourself to the Balanda way of doing things. You must run with both. You must also hold on to our own language as well. Don’t discard it and go to the white language, no. If you move too far away (from our traditions), you'll lose the Law, our law.
They’ve said to them, “Right, you just move on. You white people move on, its our turn" (to get the jobs, etc).
translation: 1. move 2. make forward progress, move on 3. make way, make room

examples: Med yirrin!
Dingihdi.
Minj diwirrinj.
Ngudda bale yihrri?
Yekke kabalemdi [kunj], yekke nakka bonj.
Bale yiyime kela? Ngunehdi?
Stay there, wait. (lit. you sing. stand imper.)
He stood there for some time.
She wasn't there.
Where have you been?
In yekke season [kangaroos] are fat, certainly in yekke season.
What kinship relationship are you to Kela? Do you call him brother-in-law?
translation: 1. stand 2. be present 3. be in affinal relationship

examples: Dilebang nakka djenj kilekilelh yiman nadjirrkku dja kukbuyika. Korroko nawu dabborrabbolk birringuni nawu dilebang.
(Andrew Manakgu, Injalak Arts painting documentation)
Rainbow fish are small, like glassfish but different. In the old days, people used to eat them.
Djal bimwi yuwurrinj yiman delek bolkki ngahbimbom wolewoleh kunekke ngayimeninj kunkudji dilh dilh dilh.
(Mick Kubarkku, on file “Transcript of cassette RA93-2” by Murray Garde, 1993.)
There was only (solid figure) images in white ochre like I use today and like I painted before with dots, one by one, dot dot dot.
Yoh dilhdilhmeninj la ngaleng Mardayin birrirarrkwemeninj mankarre nawu nadjamun 'old fashion one'.
Yes, he used to paint dots but for Mardayin ceremony they used 'rarrk' (cross hatching) which was the old fashioned way.

Bonbon kabirringun djenj nawu kilekilelh yiman marrngunj burd djakolk nawern nawu djenj kare kore kukku kubowinjku. Karrbennan birriwern kore kukku kabirridjuhmiyindi kabirridimhme kanjdji kore kukku kabirriyawan djenj kabirridanjbun kundang bedberre wanjh kabirringun.
(Andrew Manakgu, Injalak Arts painting documentation)

Cormorants eat small freshwater fish, like baby eel-tailed catfish, spangled grunter and purple spotted gudgeon. We see lots of them in the water, diving down under the water to look for fish and spearing them with their beaks and eating them.
Wam nang kabenehbokyo, wanjh med dingihdi burrbuhburrbuni.
(Mangiru, Hannah, ‘Nabangardi bidbom kuwardde’, in “Kunwinjku Stories”, Oenpelli Literature Production Centre, 1982)
He went and saw that their footprints were there, then stood there a while thinking.
translation: stand or be somewhere for a long time

examples: Djal Mann River. Nawu Dinjhmi Bokmarnde, anekke Mann River.
Still on the Mann River. Those Dinjhmi and Bokmarnde clans are on the Mann River.
Ngad karrinjilngmak bu dird kabolkwolkan, wanjh karribolknan bu kukak, nungka kayawoyhmimbimen.
(Nganjmirra, Nawakadj, ‘Kunwinjku Spirit’, Melbourne University Press, 1997, p. 120)
Nanih nawu Djabbo, dja Dird, benedangwerreni, bu dabborrabbolk ngandimarneyolyolmeng.
(Nganjmirra, Nawakadj, ‘Kunwinjku Spirit’, Melbourne University Press, 1997, p. 120)
Ngamadbom nakudji dird.
(Nganjmirra, Nawakadj, ‘Kunwinjku Spirit’, Melbourne University Press, 1997)
We are happy when the moon lights up the sky, so we can see at night. The moon comes back to life [every night].
Djabbo the Quoll had an argument with Dird the Moon. The old people told us that story.

Dirdko karrire.
Bu dirdko wanjh kabirriwaralnarren, yiman kayime mak kundung bu koyek dja karrikad bu kadungdi wanjh kabirriwaralnarren.

There's a bright moon, let's go hunting echidnas.
Wurdurd beh ngurridirri kandibengbun.
You kids go and play over there, you're driving me crazy.
Ngarrbek dja Ngalmangiyi benemdolkkang kakbibeh.

(Manakgu, Andrew, ‘Bu Ngurriborlhme Kunwinjku: Learning Kunwinjku’, Kunwinjku Language Centre, Gunbalanya, 1994)
Ngalbu ngalkordow ngalka mayh ngadberre bu ngarringun bu korrokoni dja bolkkime larrk.
(Andrew Manakgu, Injalak Arts painting documentation)
Ngurrurdu korroko dolkani rey kaddum kaluk bininj benebokenh yimankek beneyameninj dja larrk.
(Andrew Manakgu, Injalak Arts painting documentation)
Bu Kudjewk wanjh birringimi kuwardderurrk birriyoy dja mandjewk dja birndu.
(Andrew Manakgu, Injalak Arts painting documentation)
The Echidna and the Long-necked Turtle came down from the north.
You look after the kid, and I’ll go hunting for us.

In the wet season they moved into caves to stay, because of the rain and mosquitos.
Yiman nawu koyek nakka wanjh bindiyameng dalukkenh daluk bindikilekmi bindiberlmangi wanjh kunekke bindiyameng nawu birribuyika Djabbani.
There in the east, that’s where they speared them because they were interfering with women, sexually exploiting the women and so that’s why they speared those foreigners, those Japanese.
Nanih nawu Djabbo, dja Dird, benedangwerreni, bu dabborrabbolk ngandimarneyolyolmeng.
(Nganjmirra, Nawakadj, ‘Kunwinjku Spirit’, Melbourne University Press, 1997, p. 120)
Djabbo the Quoll had an argument with Dird the Moon. The old people told us that story.

Kadjabdi lorrkkon.

Yirrulkdjabnamen wanjh yirrukka midjikked.
Place some sticks in the ground and tie up your mosquito net.
Djaddedde kangun kunmalaworr. Kubolkwern ngarrbennan.
Grasshoppers eat leaves. You can see them anywhere.
Burarr nang djaddi nayahwurd. Binjolhmeng.

Mandjewk ka-djakdung djaddi 'noise' kamarnbun 'kodwong-kodwong'.

In the wet season the frogs make noise 'gotwong-gotwong'.
Nawu bininj djadmudni wam korroko, dja wanjh bolkkime mey daluk.
(Jill Nganjmirra)
The man was single for a long time, but now he's found a wife.
Djak nganbayeng.
(Dakgalawuy, Nancy, ‘Wurdyaw dirrihdirri’ in ‘Kunwinjku Stories’, Oenpelli Literature Production Centre, Gunbalanya, 1982)
Bu njale karringun karribawon kore kunrurrk wanjh karrinan nawern djak bu kanome dja kabolkan.

(Quoted in Etherington, Steve, ‘Learning to be Kunwinjku: Kunwinjku people discuss their pedagogy’, PhD Thesis, Charles Darwin University, 2006 )
Nja, ten dollar djal bonj, wardi kanmarneyakwon.

Yidjalbun.
Djal munguyh kabenedjarrkdi.

Ngamdjalbom.

Wanjh nunganwali wurdyaw kamayhmakmen - kadjalre nawu kambun mayh. Kaluk minj bidlarrk kamdurndeng.

We can’t see Nakurrurndilhba spirits, only clever men with special powers can see them.
It's just the same for the women - there are two laws they have to follow: one black, one white.
Here you are, here's ten dollars and that's it, or you'll clean me out.
Keep hitting it.
They just stay together permanently [as a couple].
"Yuwn yikan mankukyahwurd makka" "Bonj warribo ngadjalkan ngakinje ngangun. Bonj bu mankukyahwurd"
The child in turn will become a good hunter, he just goes and gets an animal, and he never comes back empty handed.

examples: Danjbom djalaban.
(The example phrase comes from texts Peter Carroll has deposited with AIATSIS)
He speared it with a 'djalaban' type spear.

Bolkkime nawu djalakiradj karrimarnbun nawu balanda marnbom wire. Karridjobke karrimarnbun dad danjbik kunubewu kunkarrngbakmeng nawu wire dad. Karrimang mankole wanjh karridadname nawu dad djalakkiradj.

Ngad ngarridjalama, Kundjalama ngarriwokdi.
We people of Djalama clan speak our own clan dialect called Kundjalama.

Korroko nawu dabborrabbolk birribimbuni kore dolobbo wanjh birrirey birriyawani djalamardi. Wanjh birrimangi birrikani kured, birridongi yika birribayeyi birrikerlkwoni. Wanjh birribarungi nawu dolobbo birribimbuni njale.
(Andrew Manakgu, Injalak Arts painting documentation. )

In the old days, when people wanted to paint on bark, they would go looking for tree orchids. They would get them, take them home and pund them up, or chew them to make them soft. Then they would paint something on the bark (using the orchid as fixative).
translation: 1. tree orchid, dendrobium orchid 2. species similar to tree orchid

examples: Nawu djalangkarridj-djalangkarridj bu kabirrinan nawu dabborrabbolk wanjh kabirriyime bonj wanjh djenj kamulewan.
(Andrew Manakgu, Injalak Arts painting documentation. )
When people see dragonflies, they say that means there are fish (ready to be caught).
Djalarr djang bedberre birri-Madjba.
The centipede is a dreaming for Madjba (Jawoyn) clan people.
Yidjalay.
Nawu Nawamud bimarneyimeng Nangarridj mah ngudda wanjh yidjalay kurih kakbi.
(Jill Nganjmirra)
Mah yidjalay munguyh yidjalmarnbu.
(Jill Nganjmirra)
Keep going further.
Nawamud said to Nangarridj "OK, you just keep on going north then".
OK just keep on doing it.
Yidjalay.
Bu bininj kabirriwohre kunbarnangarrakuyeng yiman malamalaywi kabirridedjdjingmang kabirridjale kadungborledme bu kabaldungyibme.
(Jill Nganjmirra)

Nawu bininj kabiwabun nabuyika bininj wanjh kadjalkukyakmen minj nangale kabingalke. Kunekke birrikurduyimi korroko nawu dabborabbolk bu bindiwabuni namarndekah wanjh birridjalkukyakmeni minj mak birridurndeyi kore kured dja wanjh birridjaley kore kuwardderurrk munguyhmunguyh.
(Jill Nganjmirra)
Keep going further.
When people walk around all day, for example they might start in the morning and keep on going until the afternoon and the sun starts to go down.

When a man curses another man, the other man just disappears, nobody can find him anymore. That's what people used to do in the old days, they would sing people over to the evil spirits, and they would just disappear and not come back home, they would just go on into a cave and stay there forever.
Wanjh nawu ngalmangiyi dja kedjebe nakka benewilkdi wanjh benehni benehmadbuni wanjh bu djolengminj wanjh benewayhkeng benedjalkmey benenguneng wanjh beneworrkminj.
(Garnarradj, Elaine N, ‘Ngalbadjan dja Ngalyaw’, Oenpelli Literacy Centre, Oenpelli, 1975)
Then they cooked the long-necked turtles and file snakes in the ground oven, sat and waited a while, and when they were done they lifted them out, cut them up, ate them and were full.
translation: cut into pieces, cut up, slice in half

examples: Ngabendjalwohkan wurdurd.
Manmekbe ngadjalwohyolyolmeng bonj, la ngaburnbun.
(Quoted in Etherington, Steve, ‘Learning to be Kunwinjku: Kunwinjku people discuss their pedagogy’, PhD Thesis, Charles Darwin University, 2006)
Karridjalohwamwi karrikowerrinj.
I'll take the children for the time being [until you return].
That's all I had to say, I'll stop now.
We just went there for nothing, we were under an incorrect belief (that something could be obtained there).
translation: 1. just, for the time being 2. just

examples: Yidjongburren djalawarra!
Put on those trousers!
Ngalbininjkobeng nabininjkobeng benewam kalawan benehyawani wanjh benengalkeng nawu kalawan. Ngalbininjkobeng yimeng "Mah yima yidjambarrhmang".
(Jill Nganjmirra)
Ngandjambarrhdjambarrhmang muddikang.
A husband and wife went looking for goannas, and they found one. The wife said "Okay, grab it (by the tail) and smash it against something" [this is the usual way to kill a goanna].
The truck is throwing me around.
translation: hit or throw something against something

examples: Nadjamun minj karriyolyolme.
That's secret/sacred, we don't talk about that.
Manme manbu mandjan.
(Jill Nganjmirra)
Manbu manbodjan ngarriyime makka minj kakarrme nawu mankung namanjmak. Nawu mankung ngarriyime minj manbomanjmak. Dja manbodjan.
(Jill Nganjmirra)
Bland food, food that's not very sweet.
We can describe honey that's not very good as 'manbodjan' ('liquid that's not sweet'). It's not good honey, it's a bit flavorless.
Nguddu yidjandi ngadberre!
(Jill Nganjmirra)
You’re bludging off us!
Nawu Manimunak wirlarrk djang kahdjangdi kore kaddum kuwarde Arrkuluk.
(Andrew Manakgu, Injalak Arts painting documentation)
Djalarr djang bedberre birri-Madjba.

The djalarr centipede is a dreaming for Madjba (Jawoyn) clan people.
translation: 1. totemic site, dreaming, sacred site 2. totemic emblem, dreaming

Nakudji wam djangkang, nang dungyibmeng wanjh keleminj.
A man went out hunting, saw that the sun had set and became frightened.

Manmakkawarri djang kahdjangdi kondah kore Kunbarlanja. Korroko dabborrabbolk nawu kondah kunred bedberre birrirey kunworr mandubang birrimangi birriwodbuni birridjangweyi wanjh kolungi kore manlabbarlkimuk nawu nawern djenj manmakkawarri.
(Andrew Manakgu, Injalak Arts painting documentation)

There is a sacred site for the Catfish here in Gunbalanya (a rock not far from the billabong). In the old days, the people from this area would go and hit the rock with ironwood branches as an increase ritual, and lots of catfish would go down into the billabong.
Ngaye ngawarnyak makka yaldanj, minj ngadjare.
(Maralngurra, Dolly, ‘Nakudji Namarladj Ngiwkmihngiwkmirey’, Oenpelli Literature Production Centre, 1974)
I don't want that waterlily root, I don't like it.
Bu korroko nakka mandanj birrimarnbuni kundulk birrimirrhmarnbuni. Wanjh kore mankole birridjarlkkennami wanjh djenj birridanjbuni.
(Andrew Manakgu, Injalak Arts painting documentation. )
Key yidjalkkennamen kure murrika.
Kandjalkkenname kuburldjarn.
Konda ngadjalkkennamerren.
In the old days people would make mandanj type spears. They would sharpen small pieces of wood and attach them to a spear shaft and spear fish.
Put the key in the car [in the ignition].
Put me in the middle [of a queue, or a line of dancers].
I'll put myself in the middle [of the queue].
Nabulanj wam kabbal wanjh nawu djarrang dja nganabbarru mirndeyarlarrkeng.

(Quoted in Etherington, Steve, ‘Learning to be Kunwinjku: Kunwinjku people discuss their pedagogy’, PhD Thesis, Charles Darwin University, 2006 )
Yolk mak kabebme kore ngad kunburrk kadberre bu karridowen dja kore mayh kadowerren kanudmen.
(Andrew Manakgu, Injalak Arts painting documentation)
We will all be dead and gone, and then they will look after it (the country) in turn.
Maggots come out of our bodies when we die, and also when animals die and rot.

Nakudji birrikorndowkkeng wanjh mimborledmeng doweng.
(Iyuna, James, 'Birriburrinj', Maningrida, N.T.: Maningrida Community Education Centre, 1990.)
Korroko dabborrabbolk birrirey kore kudjorlok manlabbarl birrinani djakarna kangun djenj wanjh birridanjbuni djalakkiradj dja bolkkime mako karridulubun karridowkke manbu balanda marnbom.
(Andrew Manakgu, Injalak Arts painting documentation)
Who fired that shot?
They kicked one in the groin [busted his balls], his eyes rolled and he collapsed.

In the old days, people would go down to the billabongs and see jabirus eating fish, and they would spear them with multi-pronged spears. But these days we shoot them with guns, we fire guns made by non-Indigenous people.

Kudjaborrng is the place where the ancestral woman my MMM a Durlmnagkarr clanswoman was bitten by the Oenpelli python.
translation: father-in-law, also MMM(B) and (Z)DDS; FFM(B) and (Z)SSS

examples: Ngakebdubbe.
Manberrkdubbe.
Kawarddedubbe.
Ngadjarlandubbe.
Yikanemdubbe!
Yiberddubbe!
My nose is blocked.
Dense forest, difficult to walk through.
Rough dissected sandstone country with many large boulders making travel very difficult or impossible.
I am unable to urinate. [djarlan 'bladder’ dubbe 'blocked']
Can't you hear?
Karridubbedong minj bale karriyime.
Karridubberrong yiman bolkkime karridi, karridubbedoy wanjh. Dja bu bewh wurd karribalderrehme.
(Quoted in Etherington, Steve, ‘Learning to be Kunwinjku: Kunwinjku people discuss their pedagogy’, PhD Thesis, Charles Darwin University, 2006)
We can’t pass through, it’s impenetrable, what can we do?
We don’t know which way to go at present, as we are now, we're stuck. We need to make progress.
translation: 1. be unable to pass 2. be blocked, be stuck

examples: Med, ngabengdubberranj.
Ngakebdubberranj.
Hang on, I've forgotten (can't think of it).
My nose is blocked.
translation: become blocked, become dysfunctional (of physical senses etc)

(Andrew Manakgu, Injalak Arts painting documentation )

When snails die and leave their shell behind, women used to make necklaces from the shells and dance with them in the Wubarr Ceremony. If we're walking around the forest, we sometimes see lots of snail shells in the bower of djuwe, the Great Bowerbird
Nawu bininj daluk wurdyaw ngad karrikukburlerri bu bolkkime karridowen wanjh kandidudjeng kore kurorre.
(Andrew Manakgu, Injalak Arts painting documentation )
Ngarridudjengi manme.
(Quoted in Etherington, Steve, ‘Learning to be Kunwinjku: Kunwinjku people discuss their pedagogy’, PhD Thesis, Charles Darwin University, 2006)
Nowadays when Bininj people die, men, women or children, we're buried in the ground.
We used to plant vegetables.
Manme birringeybuni ngadberre, manu, bu kundulk kore barnemdi, dja manu kanjdji dudjendi yiman kayime karrbarda, mankinjdjek, mankongkong kandirakelbukkani.
(Quoted in Etherington, Steve, ‘Learning to be Kunwinjku: Kunwinjku people discuss their pedagogy’, PhD Thesis, Charles Darwin University, 2006)
They would tell us the names of foods, the kinds that grow on trees, and the sorts that are under the ground, like long yams, round yams and Ipomea tubers. They would teach us about the plants.
translation: be buried, be under the ground

examples: Aa nakka wam dudmey manimunak!
(Jill Nganjmirra)
Nawu bininj yimeng "Ngaye dudmang rowk ngudberre".
(Jill Nganjmirra)
Djenj barrirdurdmey kalerrh, bikku, kanbaldjdja.
((Kundedjnjenghmi))
He went and got a big mob of geese!
The man said "I'll come and pick you all up" [to take you to the ceremony, etc.]
They got a big mob of fish, long-toms, catfish and eel-tailed catfish.
translation: get a lot of something, get a big mob, be successful in hunting

examples: Kukmey kunj mudkinjeng. Wanjh njamduhkeng mey kundurddu kundiw kundayken dja mannjam.
(Maralngurra, Dolly, 'Bininj Yameng Kunj', Oenpelli Literature Production Centre)
He took the kangaroo and singed its fur off. Then he opened up its belly, taking out its heart, liver, kidneys and stomach.
Karrimang nawu kunj karribardngorrowke karribiddukkan.
(Andrew Manakgu, Injalak Arts painting documentation)
Wanjh yimankek birrikuyinkelelobmerrinj Ngalyod bennanganang kunberd bendukkang rowk.
(Quoted in Carroll, Peter, 'The old people told us : verbal art in Western Arnhem Land' (Thesis), University of Queensland, 1996)
Balanda yimarnekarrewarrewon wanjh ngundukkan djamun.
(Quoted in Etherington, Steve, ‘Learning to be Kunwinjku: Kunwinjku people discuss their pedagogy’, PhD Thesis, Charles Darwin University, 2006)
We get a kangaroo and break its leg joints, then tie its limbs together (to facilitate cooking).
Then they tried to run away in fear but the Rainbow Serpent was watching them and she wrapped her tail around them.
If you break the Balanda law, the police will put you in handcuffs.
translation: 1. tie up, wrap 2. wrap up, coil around 3. put in handcuffs

examples: Manburrba yidedjdukkarrimen!
Duberrk nawu doweni wanjh ngalng birrimarnbuni kunkomkenh nawu morlehmorlenj bu Wubarr yoy wanjh birrikomdukkarreni kore kukom bedberre wanjh birriyiborrkkeyi namekke duberrk ngalng dorrengh.
(Andrew Manakgu, Injalak Arts painting documentation)

Benebokenh Ngalyod benemhwam kore wadjbudbeh benewam Katherine Gorge Nitmiluk. Bu benehrey benehdjarrkrey darnkih wernkih wanjh benedukkarrinj kunbardmo berrewoneng benebardmodukkarrinj kore kanjdji manbu kukku kahbodjurrhbume kore kunred kabolkngeyyo Marlkawo.
(Andrew Manakgu, Injalak Arts painting documentation)
Birribuyika minj balemane birribebmeninj, bonj birriruy birridoweng
Tie up your naga!
When snails die and leave their shell behind, women used to make necklaces from the shells, tie them around their necks and dance with them in the Wubarr Ceremony.

Two Rainbow Serpents came from the sea to Katherine Gorge, Nitmiluk. They travelled together very close to each other, then they entwined their bodies under the waterfall at the place called Marlkawo.
Some of the others had no where to get away and so in the end were burned, writhing to death.
translation: 1. tie onto one's body (clothes etc.), fasten (belt) 2. coil up, writhe, entwine

examples: Benewam dja benengalkeng namekbe donkey yaw dukkayindi kuberrk kore manbolh.

Nabulanj wam kore kured bidulkkimey Nawakadj nawu dulkkiyoy wanjh bikang kore clinic.

Nobody throws rocks, breaks the trees, eats the fruit or drinks the water in that place. Otherwise they would get sick themselves [like the Ancestors who got sick there].
Wernhdulmukminj nawu mandjewk.

Ngardduk kundjak kahdulmukmen.
(Nganjmirra, Nawakadj, ‘Kunwinjku Spirit’, Melbourne University Press, 1997)

My sickness is getting worse.

At Ngalkirdimu, there is a gorge you can see, that's Bod Kadjangdi, yes a gorge. That's then for the Burdoh clan. The lower area [in the catchment] is Durlmangkarr and up on top to the east is Rol clan. The hills there are for Durlmangkarr but once you're on top that's yirridjdja moiety Rol estate.
Yimdurnde!

We pound and knead the [pieces of cooked stingray] flesh, then we put it aside and cook the fat in a different drum. Then we take the flesh and the fat, mix them and eat it.
Njalekenh birridurrinj?
What were they fighting about?
Bu korroko ni bininj ngad karrikukburlerri birridjareni mankung wanjh birrirey birridjuhmi kore mankabo birridalkdurrkmangi kore mankod kore Wakkewakken wanahwam.
(Andrew Manakgu, Injalak Arts painting documentation)

Kundulk ngadedjmaddurrkme.

Wanjh mandjad bindimunkekadjungi dja bindimarnebebmi.
(Jill Nganjmirra)
Durruyuk kabirriyorrohme ba kabirriburrbun bale kabirrire.

Then when others found their campsite, they would see the mark, which would let them know which direction people had gone in. They could follow them and come directly to where they were.
They make a ground mark by dragging their feet in a line so other people will know where they have gone.

examples: Waw, nganbayeng duruk!
Kabirrire kabirribekkan kangokme duruk bu kangalke, ngalekke ngarrbek.

Korroko duruk birrikebkani, nomi nawu kalawan, birribuni.
(Andrew Manakgu, Injalak Arts painting documentation )
Ah, the dog bit me!
They walk along and hear the dog bark when it finds an echidna.
In the old days they used to take a dog when they went hunting, it would sniff out a goanna and they would kill it.
Kubolkduwa bukka.
(John Mawurndul in ''I am the old and the new': the stories behind the masterworks of John Mawurndjul', www.theguardian.com, 10/07/2018.)
That place is associated with the Duwa moiety.
Delek nakka kukbele ngarrimang duyh yika nguk ngarrimang.
(Andrew Manakgu, Injalak Arts painting documentation)
We can collect white clay when it’s dried out and powdery, and also when it’s wet.
Kab ngarre ngarrnan
(Nganjmirra, Nawakadj, ‘Kunwinjku Spirit’, Melbourne University Press, 1997, p. 148)
Let’s go and have a look
Ngad kabbal konda warddeyak.
Wanjh daluhdaluk kabirrimang kubba bedberre wanjh kabbal kabirrire kabirriyawan ngalmangiyi kabirrimang.
(Andrew Manakgu, Injalak Arts painting documentation)
We are plains people, there is no stone country here.
Then women take their turtling sticks and go out onto the floodplain to find turtles [by poking the mud with the sticks].
Kuhni bu kunkare korroko duninjh manbu kabbala Mangkadjarra birrimwam nawu Malayu birribidbom wadjbud kore Nalaberrberr dja mak kore kubolkbubuyika wadjbud.
(Andrew Manakgu, Injalak Arts painting documentation)
A long time ago people came here by boat from Macassar, those Malay people arrived on the beach at Nalaberrberr and other beaches too.

Korroko bininj birrini kunred Kabbari / Nawu kunborrk birrikarmi birriborrkkeyi (Wildflower Band, Kabbari (A Place Called Kabbari) 2009) \xe A long time ago people lived on this land Kabbari / They used to have special ceremonies, singing and dancing in that place (Wildflower Band, Kabbari / A Place Called Kabbari, 2009)

(Jill Nganjmirra)

examples: Nahni kabbay, kabirrimang kore kundulkbarndad beh, mandubang kundulk. Wanjh kabirriwirrkme, yerreh wanjh kabirrikinje kore kunak bu kabelebelbme kabirrimarnbun yiman kayime borndok, karramalk, dja wirlam.
(Jill Nganjmirra)

Ironwood resin is extracted from the roots of the ironwood tree. People scrape the bark off, then heat the wood over a fire [until the resin comes out]. They use it to stick things together, for example in making spearthrowers, stone axes, and bark rafts.
Manih bus kamrlobme manu mankebkabbungurr.
(Jill Nganjmirra)
The bus is coming, the vehicle with the flat front (literally "with a nose like a goby").
translation: 1. sleepy cod, Oxyeleotris lineolata 2. flathead goby, Glossogobius giuris

examples: Kunkare bu bininj ngad daluk dja wurdwurd bu kundjak benmangi yiman kebdjirned, wanjh birrirey birrinani kabo wanjh birrimangi birrikani kukku birridjuhkeyi birribonguni wanjh birrimakmeni.
(Andrew Manakgu, Injalak Arts painting documentation. )
Ngarradj nawu kabo nakka, Yarriwurrkkarr, yiman kayime ngad.
(Quoted in Etherington, Steve, ‘Learning to be Kunwinjku: Kunwinjku people discuss their pedagogy’, PhD Thesis, Charles Darwin University, 2006)

In the old days, when any Bininj man, woman or child was sick with something like a cold, then they would go looking for green ants, put them in water and drink the mixture and then they’d get better.
The white corella is from the Green Ant matry, Yarriwurrkkarr, just like us.

Kabulwarnamyo makka kunred kabolkngeyyo, kore bolkkime bininj kabirrihni. Kerrekenh birribolkngeybuni Norne, wanjh birringeyborledkeng manu kunbolkngey duninjh birribolkngeykurrmeng Kabulwarnamyo. Dja manbu Norne makka djang, mankung djang. Korroko dabborrabbolk birriyimi.
(Jill Nganjmirra)

Kabulwarnamyo is the name of a country, where there are currently people living. People used to call it Norne for a while, but they changed the name back to its proper place name, Kabulwarnamyo. 'Norne' is the name of a djang [in that area], it's a sacred area for honey. That's what the old people told us.
translation: Kabulwarnamyo, outstation in the Liverpool River region

examples: Ngalbadjan bimarneyimeng wurdyaw ngalengarre “Yimray kabun”.
(Jill Nganjmirra)
Ngad bininj ngarridaddornamerren kumekke wurdyaw ngarriyawkurrme kore kundad ngadberre bu ngarrikabun.
(Jill Nganjmirra)
Manimunak kakabun wirlarrk.
(Jill Nganjmirra)
The mother said to her child "Come here, I'll hold you".
We cross our legs and put our young children on our lap, and hold them like that.
The magpie goose is sitting on eggs.
translation: 1. hold a child close 2. sit on eggs

You've really made it well.

These are the tracks of a freshwater crocodile. Wait for me while I swim out and have a look for it.

Mengerrdji people used to be at Oenpelli.
Bu benewam benekang kundjabarrk dja kunbarlkbu.
(Mangiru, Faith, ‘Kakkak dja Wurdyaw Benewam Mankinjdjek’, Oenpelli Literacy Centre, 1976)
The two of them took string bags and digging sticks along.

Yiddok yibarndorrkbabang?
Ngabarndorrklurlme.
Are your glands tender?
My lymph nodes are swollen.

Minj ngarrbenngeybun yabok wardi kunbeng.

Marla nakka nabang bu kanbaye dja kandong kunberd ngalengarre.

Kunberl nganmarnebom.
He broke my arm.
Malamalaywi ngarridolkkan ngarrinan kunberle kayo.
(Jill Nganjmirra)
Konhda karriyonginj kunberle kankarrmeng.
(Jill Nganjmirra)
We get up in the morning and see that there is dew.
We slept here and got covered with dew.
Ngalbu bonbon ngarringeybun boken mayhmayh ngalkudji ngalmudburlerri dja ngalberrekalkbele ngalbuyika ngaldjalmudbulerri.

Birribidkurrmerreni kore kunwardde wanjh birrikuykmi kunbid bedberre delek dorrengh wanjh birribidbokyoy kunbidbok bedberre.

examples: Kunkarrngbakmeng or kunbidkukudji mandjewk wanjh, ngarrimdurndi ngorengngalmeng, doweni wanjh.

It picked up the scent of an animal.

Nakka nawu kundalk kawunghme.
(Quoted in Etherington, Steve, ‘Learning to be Kunwinjku: Kunwinjku people discuss their pedagogy’, PhD Thesis, Charles Darwin University, 2006)

(Andrew Manakgu, Injalak Arts painting documentation)
Yirrangbalhmen!
He put white ochre in his mouth, then sprayed it out over his hand so he made a hand stencil on the paper.
Close the door!
Dangwelburlurlhmeng.
His lip has swollen up.
Duh karriraray.
Yinjarrakinjemen.
Duh let's go [duh= Balngarra clan kundangwok].
Cook it "njarra"! [njarra= Djordi clan kundangwok]
Wanjh njamduhkeng mey kundurddu kundiw kundayken dja mannjam.
(Maralngurra, Dolly, 'Bininj Yameng Kunj', Oenpelli Literature Production Centre)
Kare odjbel kundayken nuye kabirrinan.
Then he pulled out its innards, taking its heart, its liver, its kidneys and its stomach.
He is going to the hospital and they will look at his kidneys.
Kundebi ngabenbukkabukkang kabirriburrbun.
(Quoted in Etherington, Steve, ‘Learning to be Kunwinjku: Kunwinjku people discuss their pedagogy’, PhD Thesis, Charles Darwin University, 2006)
Ngabenbekken nahni wurdwurd nawu kabirrihre minj Kundebi kabirrikarrme.
(Quoted in Etherington, Steve, ‘Learning to be Kunwinjku: Kunwinjku people discuss their pedagogy’, PhD Thesis, Charles Darwin University, 2006)
I’ve been teaching them Kundebi, they know it.
I hear these children going about – they don’t have Kundebi. No. They just use people's names. They don’t use Kundebi with each other, no.
Badjkid kabirrimarnbun dedjdjurduhdjurduh.
(Jill Nganjmirra )
They make baskets with round bases.
Merridjdjin kurredjmimken.
(Garde, Murray (ed.), ‘Bininj Gunwok talk about health : medical terms and vocabulary for health professionals’, Gundjeihmi Aboriginal Corporation, Jabiru, 2010)
Suppository.
Birrinahnani Wirrihwirrihyak nawu dengelurlmeng manbik bimarneni kore kurrenge nuye.
(Nganjmirra, Jill & Tildemann, Sonia, ‘Old Woman Emu and other Kunwinjku stories’, Batchelor Press, Batchelor, N.T., 2005, p. 6)
Dengekerlkdanj ngadberre.
They looked after Wirrihwirrihyak, whose foot was swollen because he had a splinter in his foot.
Our tyre is flat.
Mudkinjeng wanjh njamduhkeng kunnjam, kundurddu, kundiw dja kunbalem.
(Manakgu, Andrew, ‘Kunbalak : stories for Kunwinjku young people in Mother-in-law language, ordinary Kunwinjku and English’, Kunwinjku Language Centre, Gunbalanya, 1996, pp. 44-47)
He singed its [the kangaroo’s] fur, then took out the guts, heart, liver and fat.
Wurdwurd benekilekilelh benebokenh benewam benehkarungi mankuladj. Benehkarungi mankihkimuk, benedahkendoy kore kundjabarrk.
(Mangiru, Hannah, ‘Kuhni Kayolyolme Bu Kabirriwarlbunkenh’, Oenpelli Literature Production Centre, Gunbalanya, 1974 )
Two little children went digging up spike rush corms. They dug up some big ones and put them in a string bag.
Kundjaberle kunj birrimangi wanjh birrimilungi.
(Jill Nganjmirra)
They would take a kangaroo’s shoulder blade and use that to cut vegetables into thin pieces.
Lanka kure bolk-Kalarrdju kundjak djang kahyo.
Nahni manimunak kahdowen, kundjak kakarrme lead-beh, manmim shotgun nguneng.
At the place Lanka in Kalarrdju clan estate there is a sickness dreaming site.
This magpie goose is sick, it has disease from consuming shotgun lead [pellets].
Bu korroko nawu birriyungki dabborrabbolk bu manbu kunak birriworrhmi wanjh kundulk bokenh birribakkeyi birrimarnbuni kundjakkorl kunbid bedberre birriburdebmi birriwurlhkeyi manbu kunak rungi.
(Andrew Manakgu, Injalak Arts painting documentation)

In the old days when our ancestors made fires, they would break off two sticks and make firesticks out of them. They would put one between their hands and rub and a fire would start (because of the friction against the other stick).
Nanih bininj djawurrkwernminj.
(Jill Nganjmirra)
That man has grown a beard.
Bu karrikinje wanjh kadjawuywayhme.
(Nganjmirra, Nawakadj, ‘Kunwinjku Spirit’, Melbourne University Press, 1997, ‘Yawk yawk’ story.)
When we cook them, steam comes out.
Bininj yameng nganabbarru wanjh mey mandjawak kukyilkbom mey kundjen dja kunbirrkbirrkbokenh wanjh babburlibom kore kukarlang.

Yiman kayime “base”, manbu kabirriyime Balanda bu kundjen kunwok Balanda bedberre, kabirriyime.
(Quoted in Etherington, Steve, ‘Learning to be Kunwinjku: Kunwinjku people discuss their pedagogy’, PhD Thesis, Charles Darwin University, 2006 )
A man shot a buffalo, then got a knife and cut off some meat, took the tongue and two ribs and carried it all off over his shoulder.
Like a “base” as Balanda say, speaking in their Balanda tongue, their language.
Alwanjdjuk nakka bedman Kundjeyhmi.
(George Djandjomer, quoted in Murray Garde (ed.), Something about emus : indigenous knowledge of emus from western Arnhem Land, Canberra, A.C.T. Aboriginal Studies Press, 2017, p. 73)

Kunkanj, wirlarrk, kundjikkakurrk, djenj, dja nawern nawu namakmak kabendjordmiwe, yun ngurrbenwon kandidjdjawa dja tea makka manwarre.
(Nawirridj, Grace, untitled book, Oenpelli Literature Production Centre, Gunbalanya)
Nawu wurdyaw barrken duninjh wanjh nungka kundjikkakurrk kabongun bu ngalbadjan kabidjikkawon kadjikkangun.
(Jill Nganjmirra)
Meat, eggs, breast milk, fish, all those good foods are what grows them [children] up strong. Don’t give them flour and tea, that’s bad.
Very young children drink breast milk, when their mothers breastfeed them.
Ngamokdjorlok.
I've got an ulcer.
Bikarrmeng bidjorrhdukkang kondah.
He grabbed him and held him around the trunk, here.
Ngarrbendjulngmang.
Kadjulngdjabdi.
We're getting their dust (travelling behind them on a dirt road).
The dust is rising up.

(Manakgu, Andrew, ‘Kuhni bu Kunkare Birrihwarlbuni’, Oenpelli Literature Production Centre, 1974)
Birridjaldjurlebom kundjurle kondah…
(Nganjmirra, Nawakadj, ‘Kunwinjku Spirit’, Melbourne University Press, 1997)
Then the two of them walked up and saw a nice bit of shade. One of them said “Come here, let’s sit here and eat in this good shade”.
They just put up a shelter here…
Kadjurrhbume.
Kamdjurrhre.
Ngalbu ngalyod ngalkka kumdjalrey kore manberrk, wanjh manbu kukku kundjurrh kumdjalbokimukmeni.
(Nganjmirra, Jill & Tildemann, Sonia, ‘Old Woman Emu and other Kunwinjku stories’, Batchelor Press, Batchelor, N.T, 2005, p. 70)
Waterfall.
Flood water is coming up.
The Rainbow Serpent kept coming inland, and the sea kept flooding in (behind her as she went).
Bu kabirridowen daluk bininj wurdwurd wanjh mandubang kunworr kabirrimang kabirrirurrkwolngwon kundolng dorrengh.
(Andrew Manakgu, Injalak Arts painting documentation )

Death does not scare me.

In the old days we would see people breaking open bones to get the marrow, banging the bones [on rocks, wood etc] to get the marrow out, sucking the marrow from the bones, or mixing the marrow with meat - for instance the marrow from kangaroo, buffalo, cow or magpie goose bones.
Yikanem!

Kandikanemrurrknanken.
(Garde, Murray (ed.), ‘Bininj Gunwok talk about health : medical terms and vocabulary for health professionals’, Gundjeihmi Aboriginal Corporation, Jabiru, 2010, p. 35)
Auroscope (device for seeing inside the ear with a small light).
Auroscope (literally: ‘that which they use to see our ear canal’)
Kabirrikanemrurrkkurlahbalhme.

Yiman bu nayahwurd, yika mobik, minj kawernhkanjdi nungka kadjalwohdjobke mandjawak kunwardde kunyahwurd kunkanj dja kamunkewe ba kare kakimukmen kabalemdangen.

(Andrew Manakgu, Injalak Arts painting documentation)
In the old days, when people used to go into forest hunting, they would see wild cats and kill them and eat them.

Korrokko dabborrabbolk bu birriyoy kore manberrk wanjh kundulk birridulkdadjkeyi birridulkdjabnami manbu karlang wanjh borlorl birriwarnamkurrmi yerre wanjh kunkod yika dolobbo birribarrkbuni bu birrimarnbuni kunkodbarre kore birriyoykenh.
(Jill Nganjmirra)

In old days, when people camped out in the bush, they would cut forked branches and erect them in the ground, then put cross beams between them and cover the structure with paperbark or eucalyptus bark to make a shelter for sleeping.

Kunkarlewobe korroko nawu dabborrabbolk birrimarnbuni kore mankaboberl birrikurrmi. Kaluk kundulk birrimangi birridjabdjabnami, wanjh yerre kundalk birrikurrmi, birrimarnbuni djaldangrurrkni kore djenj birringimi, dja birridjalni kumekke minj birribebmeninj.
(Jill Nganjmirra)

Our ancestors used to make fenced fish traps in the narrow tributaries of rivers. They would stick a line of sticks into the creek bed, then fill in the gaps between them with grass, in such a way that there was a hole for fish to squeeze in, but they couldn't get out again and got stuck there.
Mankung ngarrikarlkidbongun.
Yiman kabirriyime nawu kabirrire kabirribomang, mannekke manu kabirrihbonome manihmanu kunkalkkid, petrol manbu.

Birrikani kured birrikinjeyi mannjam dja ngalbu burrk. Wanjh bindiwoni nawu kured birrihni. Manbu kunkalkkid makka kabirringeybun wulud.
(Andrew Manakgu, Injalak Arts painting documentation)
We drink the nectar from the honey (of flowers).
It’s like the ones who go and steal petrol, that stuff they sniff, that juice, petrol, that stuff.

translation: 1. nectar 2. sap, juice, resin, fluid 3. diesel, petrol, fuel 4. juice, gravy 5. amniotic fluid, synovial fluid, serous fluid

examples: Bu yekke dja wurrkeng kayimerran wanjh kunkarndum kayongen. Kukak yerrih. Wanjh bu malamalaywi ngarridolkkan ngarrinan kabolkbarrkbun kunkarndum. Wanjh ngarriyime "Aa, kunkarndum kankarrme".

Kunkarndum kamre dja kukku kabokurrme.
(Jill Nganjmirra)
In the seasons of Yekke and Wurrkeng, there is fog. Also at night. And when we get up in the morning and see the land covered in fog, we say "Ah, it's all foggy".
The fog comes and leaves the ground wet with dew.
Ngalyod kawehme kuluban. Bu karrinan nawern karridulubun, karringun kunkarrk. Bu karridjalburriwe, kunukka kunwarre.

Kunkarrngbakmeng o kunbidkukudji mandjewk wanjh, ngarrimdurndi ngorengngalmeng.
(Quoted in Etherington, Steve, ‘Learning to be Kunwinjku: Kunwinjku people discuss their pedagogy’, PhD Thesis, Charles Darwin University, 2006 )

So after four or five years we came back, and he started to get sick.

A mother and her daughter went gathering Memecylon pauciflorum fruits.

That man was involved in a car crash and now he's lying there injured.

Benewam kore kulabbarl. Wanjh benemadjkurrmeng, wanjh benewurlebmeng.

Yika ngarrire kunwarddebim ngarrinan kunmayali wanjh ngarrimang.

What we call a desert is like a large, wide floodplain without trees, only dirt and sand. There's no water either, it's a dry place where the dust rises in clouds and the heat shimmers in the air. It can also look as if there is water there, like a floodplain [a mirage].
translation: 1. as well, (and) also, too 2. alternatively 3. either

Malalam ngarriyime yiman kayime kabbal mankabbalwarlah dja mankimuk. Minj kundulk kadi dja kunrorre dja kunkayalanj kadjalyo. Mak minj kukku kaboyo yiman kabolkdarlehmen ngarrinan kundjulng kadolkarren mak kamirrhmirrhme. Dja mak karrinan yiman kukku kaboyo kore kabbal.

The rain falls and gives me water.
After a number of years, people firing shotguns constantly will lead to an accumulation of lead in the billabong.
Mandjimdjim kadjordmen kore kukku kaboyo kore mankabo manwanjdjad manlabbarl.
(Andrew Manakgu, Injalak Arts painting documentation)
Mandjimdjim (water pandanus) grows where there is water, by rivers, creeks and billabongs.
Bu ngarrire manberrk ngarrinan manbu kundulk kadulkngeyyo manbirdubbirdu. Kawohdulkdjinh. Ngarridulklowkmang wanjh kukku kambobebme bu ngarribongun.
(Jill Nganjmirra)
Nawu kawolk nakka mayhmayh nawu mudburlerri dja kawohmudbele. Kakebdjinh kore kunkeb nuye.
(Andrew Manakgu, Injalak Arts painting documentation )
When we go walking in the bush, we see Melaleuca nervosa trees. Where we see a lump partway up the tree, we peel off the bark and water comes out that we can drink.
The friarbird has both dark and light sections of plumage. It has a bump on its beak.
Bu kabirriwurlhke kunak karralkrung rowk wanjh mandjong bu karung darnkih kakebdowen wanjh kunmayorrk kaworlhme wanjh kamarnbun kayawoyhwurlhme.
(Jill Nganjmirra)
When people start fires and all the grass burns, there are smouldering logs left behind, and when the wind blows them it makes them burst into flame again.

Bu Kunbarlanja ngarre, Kunbarlanja ngarrbendjawan bininj ngadjawan and bininj nakohbanj minj nakohbanj bad yawurrinj, minj kakodjbulu kadjalbengkan. Ngarridjawan konda nangale nuye kunred, 'Mandjulngunj' kayime.
Bonj wanjh konda bu konda Mandjulngunj kunred bonj manu mani ngarrbidbun nungka wanjh Maningkali manu mane manberrk.

If you and I go to Kunbarlanja and we ask people there, an old person and not just an older person, a young man also, someone who doesn't have grey hair, they would know [immediately]. If we ask 'Whose country is this [here at Kunbarlanja] he would say 'Mandjulngunj'.
This is all Mandjulngunj country here, but if we go up [upstream in the catchment] it is Maningkali- all of this open forest savanna here.
Mandjumbak kunrakken.
Calytrix achaeta is good for fire wood.
Manbu mandjungkurrk makka kundulk, dja kunmalaworr ngarrimang bu ngarrikerribun mayh yiman kunkanj nganabbarru, bulikki, kunj dja kurdukadji. Kamanjmakwon bu ngarringun kamak rowk.
(Jill Nganjmirra. )
Andjungkurrk arridarme kamanjmakmen kunkanj.
Mandjungkurrk is a kind of tree, and we gather its leaves when we cook animals in a ground oven, for example buffalo, bull, kangaroo or emu meat. It flavors the meat so it tastes good when we eat it.
We use andjungkurrk leaves to flavour meat and make it taste good. [Kundedjnjenghmi]
Bu kudjewk karrire wanjh karrihmang manu mandjurrukkumarlba.
(Narndal, Julie et. al. ‘Manme: Stories about food - Kunwinjku’, Oenpelli Literature Production Centre, 1982)
In the wet season we go and collect Antidesma ghaesembilla berries.
Wanjh benebalwam benebolknang yimankek bu kungarre benebalngimeng, benenang mandolhdolh.
(Mangiru, Hannah, 'Djakku dja Nabulanj Benewam', Oenpelli Literary Project, Gunbalanya 1976)
So they went and had a look around and were about to go into the jungle thicket. They saw some bush cucumbers.
Dja bu birridoweni wanjh birrimangi kunworr mandubang birrirurrkwolngwoni kundolng dorrengh manbu kunrurrk kore yongohyoy.
(Andrew Manakgu, Injalak Arts painting documentation)
And when someone died, then people would get leaves from the ironwood tree and smoke the place that person used to live in.
Korroko bu ngarriyawani mandudjmi ngarrimangi ngarridahkendongi kundjabarrk.
(Peter Carroll AIATSIS collection)
In the old days when we used to look for green plums, we would put them in a dilly bag.
Manbu karrbarda mandule dja kunborrk bu korroko nakudji nakohbanj dabbolk Nakangila Nabarrbinj marnbom.
(Andrew Manakgu, Injalak Arts painting documentation. )
Bedda mandulebuyika kabirriwokdi.
An old Nakangila skin man of the Barrbinj clan made the Long Yam song and dance, a long time ago.
Those people have a different accent in the way they talk.
Mandulk yiman kadulkyime mandjoh dja ngalengman manmalaworrkimuk, kadjordmen kore kukabo dja kore njilhmi. Manekke birribakkeyi dabborrabbolk bu birridjarlkkennami lulumarra.
(Jill Nganjmirra )

Mandulk is a tree similar to mandjoh (Acacia difficilis), but with larger leaves. It grows by rivers and creeks. That's the tree that our ancestors used to break off to (make spear shafts to) attach to lulumarra type spear heads.
Benewam kore mandulum kabolkngeyyo Mankarrinjdji darnkih Warruwi.
(Andrew Manakgu, Injalak Arts painting documentation. )
Kunred ngalengarre karedmarnbun kunworr, manyahyay kundulk dja kunkurlk wanjh kamornname kadulummarnbun mandulumkimuk.
(Andrew Manakgu, Injalak Arts painting documentation.)
They went to a hill called Mankarrinjdji near Warruwi.
She (the jungle fowl) makes her nest from leaves, acacia branches and earth, gathering them to make a big mound.
Korroko Manginburru bininj birrini kunred ngardduk.
A long time ago Manginburru people lived on my land.
translation: tribal name, ethnonym for Goomadeer River people, Goomadeer (Kumadderr) River catchment people

examples: Mahni mirridjdjin yingun ba bu ngunkurlbamarnbun dja mak wurdyaw ke kadjordmen.
(Garde, Murray (ed.), ‘Bininj Gunwok talk about health : medical terms and vocabulary for health professionals’, Gundjeihmi Aboriginal Corporation, Jabiru, 2010)
You should take these tablets to make your blood strong and help your baby grow properly.
Namarnde Bangolkarrmeng... ngamed nawu Wamud nuye nangamed Nayingkul, ngamed kunnguya njamed na-Manilakarr.
Namarnde Bangolkarrmeng ... belongs to Wamud, whatsisname, Nayingul, of the whatsit, Manilakarr patriclan.
Birribekkang danginj Balang birrimwokngimeng birrimanjbom.
When they heard that Balang was born they telephoned to express affection for him.
Ngalbadjan bimarneyimeng nawu wurdyaw "Yingu mahni manme manmanjmak duninjh".
(Jill Nganjmirra)
Mannguy manmanjmak.
(Jill Nganjmirra)
Mak nawu kunkukken kabirrikukbarurren nakka namanjmakkayken.
(Jill Nganjmirra)
The mother told the child "Eat up that food, it's really tasty".
A sweet smelling flower.
Also when people put on skin cream, it smells really nice.
translation: 1. delicious, sweet, tasty, good tasting 2. sweet smelling

examples: Nawu wurdurd kabirrimanjngun manbu manmanjmak manme, dja yiman kayime drink manbu kabirribomanjngun bu kabirribongun.
(Jill Nganjmirra )
Kabolkmanjngun, kadjare kumekke kahdi.
(Jill Nganjmirra)
Sunday School mak ngamanjnguni manekke and nganmarneyolyolmi manbu yiwarrudj.
(Quoted in Etherington, Steve, ‘Learning to be Kunwinjku: Kunwinjku people discuss their pedagogy’, PhD Thesis, Charles Darwin University, 2006 )
Children like like to eat sweet tasty food, and they also like to drink (soft) drinks.
He really likes that place, he wants to stay there.
Sunday School also, I used to really like that, they would tell us about the scriptures.
translation: 1. like the taste of something 2. like or enjoy something

examples: Bedda Nakorrkko benekabokurrmeng.
The Nakorrkko ancestors placed the creek there.
Bedda benenang kunwardderurrk wanjh benelobmeng kumekke benengimeng, dja mandjewk dedjdjingmey mankamankani.
(Nganjmirra, Nawakadj, ‘Kunwinjku Spirit’, Melbourne University Press, 1997)
They saw a cave, ran towards it and went in, just as the rain was starting to fall.
Benehbarndi kore kundulk kaddum mankarrarlhmanj manmim benehmimnguni.
(Andrew Manakgu, Injalak Arts painting documentation. )
The two of them were sitting up in the tree eating mankarralarlhmanj nuts.
Nungka barrk yika kayo kure mi-karrarndalk dja mi-ngarre.
Sometimes black wallaroos sleep in the spinifex and in thickets.
Kunibidji minj kabindiberddadjdje, mankarre bedberre.
Kakarrerawon.
The Kunibidji do not practice circumcision. It is their custom.
He will participate in his second ceremony (lit: 3s.+ceremony+add on).
translation: 1. custom, manner 2. culture, law 3. ceremony, song 4. message, news

examples: Nawu nawarlah nakka kakarrme mankimanki kore kaberdyirriyo.
(Jill Nganjmirra)
Mak bininj nawu namarndeyi kakarrme mankimanki bu kadjare kabenbun bininj. Kaburriwe wanjh kabidulubun nawu bininj wanjh kabekkarren bu kahbabang, wanjh kadowingalme.
(Jill Nganjmirra)
Stingrays have a barb on their tail.
A sorcerer can also use (invisible) stingray barbs to attack people. He throws the barb and it pierces the victim, who feels a pain and then begins to sicken.

Nawu dabborrabbolk nawu nayuhyungki korrokoni birribimbuni mayh nawu bim yiman kayime kunj, ngurrurdu, ngalmangeyi dja mak djenj. Dja manme warridj yiman kayime kayawal, mankinjdjek dja njalehnjale manmebuyika manu.

Those early ancestors a very long time ago painted images of animals such as kangaroos, emus, long neck turtles and fish. They also painted (in rock shelters) images of vegetable foods such as long yams (Dioscorea transversa), cheeky yams (Dioscorea bulbifera) and other kinds of foods.
translation: cheeky yam, yam sp., Dioscorea bulbifera

examples: Nahni Wakkewakken kabirriyo kore kundulk mankod kore kukabo kore manbokedjelk.
(Andrew Manakgu, Injalak Arts painting documentation)
The Wakkewakken spirits live among the paperbark trees in the river, in the cold water.
Bu karrire kumunun wanjh mankokkarrng kanwolkan kabolkwolkan kore karrire.
(Andrew Manakgu, Injalak Arts painting documentation)
When we are travelling in the dark the stars give us light, they light up the ground where we are walking.
Kuni kunkare nakudji bininj wam kabbal, kani bokenh mankole dja borndok.
(Manakgu, Andrew, ‘Kuhni bu Kunkare Birrihwarlbuni’, Oenpelli Literature Production Centre, 1974)
One day a long time ago a man went to the floodplain, he was carrying two spears and a spearthrower.
Kakolhdebebme.
(Jill Nganjmirra)
A little shoot comes up.
Korroko nawu kohbakohbanj nawu morlehmorlenj birrirey birrikarungi manbu mankongkong. Birriwilkdengi mandjoleng ngandiwoni ngarringuni.
(Andrew Manakgu, Injalak Arts painting documentation)
In the past, the old women used to go and dig up bush potatoes. They’d put them in the hot coals, and give us the cooked ones to eat.
Kundulk manbu kunkod kahkarrme ngarrinan kunmalaworr, wanjh ngarriburrbun, yiman kayime yilbinj, mandarl, mankorrko dja mandjinh.
(Jill Nganjmirra )

When we see the leaves of paperbark trees, we can recognise them, for example whether a tree is yilbinj, mandarl (Melaleuca viridiflora), mankorrko (Melaleuca argentea) or mandjinh (Melaleuca nervosa).
Yiddok mahni karringun mankuk?
(Quoted in Etherington, Steve, ‘Learning to be Kunwinjku: Kunwinjku people discuss their pedagogy’, PhD Thesis, Charles Darwin University, 2006 )
Mankurndalh ngarrinan mannguy bu kanguybun, wanjh darnkih bu kakukdangen mankuk manme.
(Andrew Manakgu, Injalak Arts painting documentation)
Can we eat this raw?
We see the black plum tree flowering, and not long afterwards young (unripe) fruits appear.
Mankuladj kadjordmen kore kabbal. Morlehmorlenj dja yawkyawk wurdwurd kabirrire kore kabbal kabirrikarung mankuladj.
(Andrew Manakgu, Injalak Arts painting documentation)
Spike rushes grow on the floodplain. Women, girls and children go to the floodplain to dig up the corms.
Wardurrkku nakka nakimuk nabadjan nakka, nawardurrkku, mankumirli, nabadjan rerre, wardurrkku, nabadjan rerre namekke boken, kangeyboken, nawu namekke nakimukken nawu.
'Wardurrkku' is a large individual, 'wardurrkku' and 'mankumirli' is also the same. These are two names for the big barramundis.
Minj ngad karrinan nawu Nakurrurndilhba birridjalkudji kabirrinan nawu marrkidjbu nawu birrikurdang.
(Andrew Manakgu, Injalak Arts painting documentation. )
We can’t see Nakurrurndilhba spirits, only clever men with special powers can see them.
translation: spiritual power, magical power, supernatural power

examples: Manbu mankurlurrudj makka kundulk manme kamarnbun bu Kurrung wanjh kurdukadji karrinan kare kamimngun manbu makurlurrudj manme manmim.
The sand palm (Livistona humilis) fruits in the dry season, and we see emus eating the seeds.
(Andrew Manakgu, Injalak Arts painting documentation)
Mankurndalh birribarndiwirrinj kamwakemeninj birriyameninj. Manekke ngayameng wanjh barnambarl.

They would stand up high in the Vitex_glabrata tree and when [the emu] came wandering over [to eat the fallen fruit] they would spear it. I speared one from up in a tree, a technique called barnambarl.
Nalodkimuk.
Yilodbakkemen.
Fat man.
Break the loaf (of damper).
translation: 1. round object, cylindrical/oblong thing, cylindrical/oblong thing, round object 2. loaf

examples: Manlombelng mandulkrayek, korroko dabborrabbolk birridulkmangi birrimarnbuni kunbarlkbu wanjh birrikarungi manme.
(Jill Nganjmirra)
The manlombelng tree has hard wood, in the old days people used to use the wood for digging sticks to dig up food.
Manmakmak manme
(Jill Nganjmirra)
Healthy food.

Bu manmile ngarriyime wanjh kunukka yiman kayime nawu kunmadj ngarrimarnbun. Marebu, djerrh, badjkid, kundjabarrk. Dja bu ngarriyime mile wanjh kunukka ngarrimilekurrme nawu ngarridahkendikenh yiman kayime balangkid.
(Jill Nganjmirra)

When we say 'manmile', we mean something woven that we're making, for example a mat, dilly bag, basket or string bag. But when we say 'mile', that means bedding that we're putting down so we can sleep in it, like a blanket.
Dedjkorrk kangun barrdjungka manmim.
(Andrew Manakgu, Injalak Arts painting documentation)
Nahni manimunak kahdowen, kundjak kakarrme lead-beh, manmim shotgun nguneng.
The the Australasian Grebe eats the seeds of water lilies.
This magpie goose is sick, it has disease from consuming shotgun lead [pellets].
Manmorlak makka kundulk dja manme kakarrme manbu ngarringun. Bu kare kanguybun kakukdangen kadjolengmen wanjh ngarrire ngarimoyhmang manbu mandjoleng kawarrawarrhme kore kurorre kukurlk.
(Andrew Manakgu, Injalak Arts painting documentation )
The billy goat plum is a tree which has edible fruits. When it flowers, the fruits form on the tree and ripen, then we go and gather the ripe fruits which fall on the ground.
Ngaye Kamarrang na-Burdoh, nani Nabarlek Band ngarduk ngaye. Konda Manmoyi kabolkngeyyo.
(Quoted in CAAMA Productions (2001). Nabarlek: Manmoyi. [video] Available at: https://www.nfsa.gov.au/collection/curated/nabarlek-manmoyi [Accessed 22 Jun. 2019].)
Nakorrkko kabenebokyo kure Manmoyi.
I'm Kamarrang of the Burdoh clan. This is the Nabarlek band here with me, and this place is called Manmoyi.
There are footprints of the Nakorrkko ancestor heroes at Manmoyi.
translation: 1. Manmoyi, Homeland centre/outstation name 2. place on Mankorlod creek

examples: Korroko kobahkobanj nawu daluhdaluk birrikani kundjabarrk wanjh birridahkendongi manngalele bu rungi manngalele kudjewk.
(Jill Nganjmirra)
In the past, the old women would take their dillybags and fill them with white currants, when the currants ripened in the wet season.
Nakka kunekke kunj kawarlkkayindi kungarre.
Birriwurlhkeng, birriwurlhkemeninj kundjahkorl bordebmeninj wurlhkeng bonj manngarre kurrmeng nawu biwurlhkeng birurrkdabkeng.
That kangaroo is there hiding in the bushes.
Manbu manngukmanj makka manme ngarringun bu ngarrikarrme kebdjirned, dja mak kala ngarrimang manbu mandulkdad bu ngarrikinje kunngobarn wanjh karlba kayimerran.
(Jill Nganjmirra)
Cheesefruit is a fruit that we eat when we have a cold, and we also get dye from the roots, cooking them up with pandanus to make the pandanus yellow.
Kabirrinjonjme manme wanjh mannjonj kayimerran.
(Jill Nganjmirra)
They pound food into a pulp.
translation: soft food which has been pounded, mincemeat

examples: Kunak karung wanjh manrakel kawelengbebme.
(Victor Garlngarr)
Fire burns (the country) and new growth will eventually come up.
Ngad ngarrikeleminj bu birrimarnbom war... Ngarriwam Warruwi rowk, ngarrinang manwern manwelyi dja kabbala kore kurrula.
(Nganjmirra, Nawakadj, ‘Kunwinjku Spirit’, Melbourne University Press, 1997)
We were scared when the war started... We all went to Goulburn Island, and saw lots of aeroplanes, and boats on the ocean.
Birradjdja ngarringuni… ngarrikurrmi, ngarribuni wanjh yoy. Manwerrk manu rey warreka.
(Quoted in Etherington, Steve, ‘Learning to be Kunwinjku: Kunwinjku people discuss their pedagogy’, PhD Thesis, Charles Darwin University, 2006)
We used to eat rice… we used to put it there and thresh it. The husks would fly off all over the place but the rice would stay where it was.
Manwodjkare karridorrorroke.
Let's drag the old logs.
Manwurrkkah birriduhdulubom kunj yo. Ngarrikarrmeng mankole nawu, bolkkime rifle.
(Kalarriya)
They used to spear kangaroos in the midst of the fire. We had spears then but today we have rifles.
Bu karrire baleh kore manberrk karriwarlbun karrirednan djuwe karedmarnbun kamang kundalk dja manyahyay kundulk.
(Andrew Manakgu, Injalak Arts painting documentation)
If we go anywhere in the forest hunting we see bowerbird nests, it makes its nest by gathering grasses and acacia branches.
translation: acacia branches, dry acacia (and other) branches

examples: Berrerdberrerd karrinan kabarndi kore kundulk manyende yika karrolkan kare kubuyika mayh kayawan.
(Andrew Manakgu, Injalak Arts painting documentaton)
Nani yina bobbidj, la ngabidbun wanjh ngarradjeng wanjh ngarradje ngayendedadjke ngayendedadjke kamankan." "Ma ma ma," bidbom wanjh yendedadjeng, yendedadjeng rowk 'wey bum' mankang.
Anyendewern
We see Rainbow Bee Eaters sitting on tree branches, or flying off somewhere else to look for insects.
You see that honey hive there, well I'll climb up and cut it, I'll cut all the branches off and it'll fall down. "Yeah OK, OK." He climbed up and cut all the branches off; 'thud', it fell down.
Lots of little tributaries or channels of a watercourse
Anyokkorlomud ankung arribarungi arridjuhkeyi arringuni ngurrurdu arrikarlkidnguni.
Manyokkorlomud makka kundalk, kadjordmen kore manbehbeberrk. Kaluk birridalkmangi bu birribarungi mankung nawu dabborrabbolk, wanjh birridahkendongi kore bulbbe, yika kolod.
(Jill Nganjmirra)
Kunj nawu kolobarr dja karndayh kabirridedjmadngun manbu kundalk manyokkorlomud.
(Jill Nganjmirra)
We used the an-yokkorlomud grass to soak up honey and to drink the gravy juice from cooked emus.
Manyokkorlomud is a type of grass that grows in open forest country. Our ancestors use to gather it to wipe up honey, and put it into (tightly woven) dilly bags or the base of palm fronds.
Male and female antilopine kangaroos eat the roots of manyokkorlomud grass.
Kore manyunkurr, adjbud kayo.
(Wildflower Band, ‘Galiwin’ku’)
On the island, there is a beach.
Yiman ngad bininj, nungka wayarra mararradj kakarrme warridj.
Just like people, wayarra spirits have boyfriends/girlfriends too.
Dja mak bu bininj kabirriwokngimen kondabeh kore Mardbalk wanjh dingki kabirrimlobme.
(Andrew Manakgu, Injalak Arts painting documentation)
And if people phone Goulburn Island from here, people will come over in a dinghy [to pick them up].

translation: prawn sp., freshwater prawn, Macrobrachium bullatum

examples: Manbu kundulk kadulkngeyyo mardderr ngalengman kadjordmen kore kukabohkabo, dja manbu kunmalaworr makka wanjh kamalaworrbume.
(Jill Nganjmirra)
The silver-leaved paperbark grows by rivers, and the leaves give off a kind of haze (as oil evaporates from them in the sun).
Nawu marebu nakka nakimuk mat kabirrimarnbun. Daluhdaluk kabirrire kunngobarn kabirrimang dja kundulk manbu mandjarnngal kabirrikan kabirrikardmang manbu kunngobarn kahdjabdi manekke kabirrimang.
(Andrew Manakgu, Injalak Arts painting documentation)

A “marebu” is a big mat which people make. Women go and get pandanus, they take a forked stick along so they can hook the pandanus leaves with it [and pull them down], the straight leaves that stand upright.
Marla nakka nabang bu kanbaye dja kandong kunberd ngalengarre.
(Andrew Manakgu, Injalak Arts painting documentation.)
Scorpions are dangerous if they bite you, they strike you with their tail.
Birridoy rowk, wanjh birrikayhmeng, "Marladj", birrimarneyimeng, "Yimray ngundiwon". Yimarnek kamkuyinwam kondanj darnkih "Ya", birrimarneyimeng, wanjh nalkiduhdurndi djalwam wanjh doweng kunmarrwe.

They pounded all the food, then they called him 'orphan boy' they said, "Come, they'll give you some." He came close up then "ya", they said to him [they tricked him and didn't give him the food] and so he went back crying and starving.
Bu mankole kabirriyamerren, bininj kabirribaye namekke marlakka ba kunyid kabenwon.
(Nganjmirra, Nawakadj, Ngaldjordboh Story in ‘Kunwinjku Spirit’, Melbourne University Press, 1997)
During spear fights, men bite these sacred dilly bags (hanging around their neck) to give them fighting spirit.
Korroko dabborrabbolk birrimarnbuni mandjabu.
(Andrew Manakgu, Injalak Arts painting documentation)
Nungkah marnbom manekke Ubarr, nungkah marnbom Yirrbardbard.
(Nganjmirra, Nawakadj, ‘Kunwinjku Spirit’, Melbourne University Press, 1997)
Ngarrimarnbuni ngadberre lesson.
(Quoted in Etherington, Steve, ‘Learning to be Kunwinjku: Kunwinjku people discuss their pedagogy’, PhD Thesis, Charles Darwin University, 2006)
Muddikang ngarduk warreminj, ngakan kore mechanic kabirrimarnbun.
Dja kore mulil kabirrikarrme kabirrimarnbun wanjh kunrodjbe kabirribarurren bininj dja daluk.
(Andrew Manakgu, Injalak Arts painting documentation )
Namarrkon kamarnbun kangurdulme kamayhke dja kandong bininj.
(Nganjmirra, Nawakadj, ‘Kunwinjku Spirit’, Melbourne University Press, 1997)
In the old days, people used to make fish traps.
He created the Ubarr ceremony, Yirrbardbard created it.
We would do our lessons.
My car has broken down, I'll take it to the mechanic and they will fix it.
When they have ceremonies, men and women (sometimes) paint themselves with red ochre.
Namarrkon makes it thunder and creates lightning and strikes people.
translation: 1. make, build, create 2. do, complete 3. fix, heal 4. organise, arrange 5. cause, force

examples: Kanmarneka manbu kunyarl.
(Nganjmirra, Nawakadj, ‘Kunwinjku Spirit’, Melbourne University Press, 1997, ‘Biyuk Biyuk’ story. )
Nja, ten dollar djalbonj, wardi kanmarneyakwon.
(Evans, Nicholas (ed.), How to write Kundjeyhmi, prepared for the National Parks and Wildlife Service and the Gagudju Association.)
Ngalngayeng kawarre nganmarnedoweng korroko ngarribarrkbombarrkbom. Ngurrimray karrimarnenalkbun.
Kumekke bimarnebebmeng biyameng.
(Manakgu, Andrew, ‘Kunbalak : stories for Kunwinjku young people in Mother-in-law language, ordinary Kunwinjku and English’, Kunwinjku Language Centre, Gunbalanya, 1996, pp. 24-27)
Bring that rope for me.
Here you are, here's ten dollars and that's enough, or you'll clean me out.
(words to a song) My daughter has died, we have been grieving all through the night until dawn. Come all of you and let us wail for her.
He appeared there where she was and speared her.
translation: 1. for, benefactive verbal prefix 2. prefix that emphasises that an action relates to a particular person

examples: Kumekke bimarnebebmeng biyameng.

Ngalkudji ngalyawk birrengedulubom kundulk minj baleh yimeninj bu rawinj dja kerlkdanj. Wanjh ngalbuyika daluk bimornemey.

The father said to the child "Come here, I'll pick you up and carry you on my back so we can go".
A girl spiked her foot on a piece of wood, and was in too much pain to walk. So another woman put her up on her shoulders to carry her.

Nangale mulewam?
Kano warde mulewan.

Who related that news?

Nawalabik killed Nangordyawok, he chopped his neck and he died. Nangordyawok's mother went back to her family and told them "Nawalabik killed my son". Then Nawalabik appeared and confessed his deed, he said "I killed Nangordyawok".
"Adju bokoluy?" "Larrk, kadjalborlobme manbomurrngbang".
(Jill Nganjmirra)
Kunmayorrkmurrngbang.

The Ngurrkdu estate belongs to the Murumburr clan, who speak Kundjeyhmi. It's an important area that many non-Indigenous people visit, to see the clan's rocks, water and forests. [Cooinda, Yellow Water etc].
A: Yes, Anbarrawarrku. Whatsisname lives there. B: A Murumburr clan place? A: Yes, Murumburr. That bloke who shoots buffalo, whatsisname, David.
Nanih nabadjan biyawmey.
This is his uncle here, the one whose sister gave birth to him (or 'is in his upper adjacent generation matriline').

translation: skin name (male), subsection (male) of duwa patri-moiety

Beh karrire.

Let's go to the same place again, to that place we always go to.

examples: Nawu nakurl nakka mandjewk. Mandjewk kamre, kadedjdjingmang bu kadjakdung kurnumeleng. Nakka wanjh ngarringeybun barra dja djimurru, nawu kukku kabokurrme bu kamarnbun kaborlobme kore mankabo mak kabobarlke kore kulabbarl. Dja mak kamarnbun kundalk kundulk dja manme manwern kakukmarnbun bu kadjordmen. Dja nawu nakurl ngarrinan koyekbeh kangolburlerran kawarnamkurrme, wanjh nakka kamre bu kundalk kakekurrme rowk, kore kurorre kayo. Dja mak kayiburnbun bu kadjakdung. Wanjh nakka ngarringeybun nakurl.
(Jill Nganjmirra)

‘Nakurl’ is a storm. The rains start in the early wet season, and we call those rains ‘barra’ and ‘djimurru’, they make the rivers flow and fill up the billabongs. They also make the grasses, trees and many fruits grow. Nakurl are the storms that we see coming from the east, the clouds darken and make a dark horizontal bar on the horizon. It comes and knocks all the spear grass to the ground. That’s at the end of the wet season, the rains stop after that.
translation: last storms of wet season, 'knock'em downs'

examples: Bu Nawalabik bibom Nangordyawok doweng wanjh ngalbadjan nuye Nangordyawok nalkirey bu durndehdurndengi kore kakbi namud ngalengarre.

When Nawalabik killed Nangordyawok, Nangordyawok’s mother went back crying to her family in the north.

(Maralngurra, Rachel, ‘Wurdwurd Bedberre’, C.M.S, Gunbalanya, 1974)

“Yes”, said his wife, “Should we all go together, with the two kids?”. But the father said “No, they can stay with grandma and grandpa, the two of us can go looking for wild honey and I’ll go hunting for kangaroo”.

“Namardaka” is a large catfish, and “marrngunj” is a small one.

Get the axe otherwise the lightning will strike it. (It is said that axes left out in a storm will attract

(Andrew Manakgu, Injalak Arts painting documentation )
Bu korroko larrwa birrimarnbuni kore kundulk dja bolkkime kabirridadjke mankole kore manbu kayingkihrurrk manekke kodj kabirriname wanjh bakki kabirrikurrme kabirrikinje kabiwungme.

(Andrew Manakgu, Injalak Arts painting documentation.)
He's painted the crocodile and fish in Kunwinjku 'xray' style, he's painted in the stomach as well.

Namomoyak gave us our wisdom, so that’s what we [still] follow.

(Wildflower Band, ‘Galiwin’ku’, from the Album ‘Manginburru Bininj’, Skinnyfish Music, 2009)
I want to go back to my home Ngardayun / where my family is staying

That snake, the black whip snake. It has two names. I call it wurrkurduk [in Kundedjnjenghmi] and others call it namung. It is aggressive and can bite us, but we don't die, it's only mildly venomous.
Yina!
Nganan.
Nan.
Nang.
Minj nganayinj.
Nangahnang.
Look!
I'll have a look.
I'm looking at you.
He saw it./I saw you.
I didn't see her.
I saw you (I was watching you).

Yoh, nanikud nawern, kabbal di kunukka… birrinahnani kohbakohbanj.

Yes, there were lots of goats. They used to be out on the plains and the old people used to look after them.

skin name (male), subsection (male) of yirridjdja patri-moiety
subsection (male) of yirridjdja patri-moiety, skin name (male)

"Ngabba ngaye ngadjare kanwernhbukkan."

After that, they would invite women to eat the kangaroos that the boy speared (the first kangaroos speared by a young man are traditionally taboo for women to eat).
Bu korroko nakudji nakohbanj dabbolk Nakangila Nabarrbinj marnbom manbu mandule karrbarda wayihwayini wanjh biyibawong nakangilabuyika Nadjalama balhwayini bu darrkidni.
(Andrew Manakgu, Injalak Arts painting documentation)
Nabangardi yolyolmi kore kunbalanda wanjh nganyibawoni ngayeman ngabenkani kore ngad karriwokdi kunwok.
(Quoted in Etherington, Steve, ‘Learning to be Kunwinjku: Kunwinjku people discuss their pedagogy’, PhD Thesis, Charles Darwin University, 2006 )
Ngalngarridj bimarneyimeng ngalbu Ngalbangardi, yimeng "Yina ngaye wanjh kukyibawong nawu djenj dja ngalmangiyi. Bimarneyimeng "bonj yikukkarrmen ba yikinje wanjh yingun."
(Jill Nganjmirra)
In the past a Nakangila skin man of the Barrbinj clan made the Long Yam song cycle, then passed it on to another Nakangila skin man of the Djalama clan, who sang it while he still lived.

Ngalngarridj told Ngalbangardi "Look, I left the fish and the turtle for you. Keep them so you can cook them and eat them".
Yibba, ngoyongoyo kakodjkeyo, kodjdjewarre kabirrimerlemyembun. Kukurlk kayo.

(Jill Nganjmirra)
Ngoyongoyo kakodjkeyo djaddi. Kakodjkewarre, kabirrimerlemyibbun.
When for example a man has some pain in some part of his body, people can rub it and the pain will stop.
The ngoyongoyo frog is a sleeping frog. It is a sleepyhead (ie. it hibernates), they rub their bellies.
Muddikang yibmeng ngadberre.
Yina, nakkan kumoken kayibme.
Our car is bogged.
Look, that freshwater crocodile is going under the water.
Yika birriyiddungi wurdwurd, birridurreni but yika mak ngarrimakni ngarridjalni yidyak.
Some kids used to get angry and fight, but some of us were good and we didn’t start fights.
Baleh yimi bu yiyidmebabangni?

How long have you had a toothache?
Namekke nadjinem manme kangun manbadbirri, yika kakolung kuwardde kakolung manbuyhbuyika kangun.
That black rock kangaroo eats Uvaria fruit, sometimes it comes down from the rocks and eats other kinds of food.
Kabirriyikadjurren rowk ngalbu kurdukadji kunkanj dja kunbalem.
(Jill Nganjmirra)
They all share the meat and fat of the emu between themselves.

examples: Wanjh bu kedjelkminj benenguneng dja yikahwi benekang kured.
(Manakgu, Andrew, ‘Kunbalak : stories for Kunwinjku young people in Mother-in-law language, ordinary Kunwinjku and English’, Kunwinjku Language Centre, Gunbalanya, 1996, p. 17)
…yikahwi bu kabindiwon kunrayek, bu kabindimarnewokdi nahni nawu teacher nawu wurdyaw ngalnjilngwarre […]
(Quoted in Etherington, Steve, ‘Learning to be Kunwinjku: Kunwinjku people discuss their pedagogy’, PhD Thesis, Charles Darwin University, 2006 )
When they [the yams from the ground oven] had cooled down they ate them, and took some of them home.
The teacher sometimes is harsh with those kids [my grandchildren]. When teachers tell them off, a child will become very unhappy.
Karrikerriyikan ba karrikerribun karrikinje kunj.

Wolehwoleh ngarriwam hospital, nakohbanj ngarriyikang.

translation: go for something, fetch, go to visit

examples: Yilbinj makka kakarrme manwern kunkod.
(Jill Nganjmirra )
Kundulk manbu kunkod kahkarrme ngarrinan kunmalaworr, wanjh ngarriburrbun, yiman kayime yilbinj, mandarl, mankorrko dja mandjinh.
(Jill Nganjmirra )
Yilbinj is a type of paperbark tree that has a lot of paperbark on it.

When we see the leaves of paperbark trees, we can recognise them, for example whether a tree is yilbinj, mandarl (Melaleuca viridiflora), mankorrko (Melaleuca argentea) or mandjinh (Melaleuca nervosa).
Wud yirrahkendo biliken wardi ngunyilkan.
Nayin nganyilkang!

Aah dulkyilkang nakka darnkih dulkdoyi!
(Jill Nganjmirra)
Put the worms in the billycan otherwise they'll slither all over you.
A snake slithered over me!
Ahh, he brushed that tree, he almost crashed into it!
Bininj yameng nganabbarru wanjh mey mandjawak kukyilkbom mey kundjen dja kunbirrkbirrkbokenh wanjh babburlibom kore kukarlang.
(Nabobbob, Rose, ‘Kunbidkudji Kunwok’, Oenpelli Literature Production Centre, Gunbalanya)
Bu kunborlidj birridjareni nawu bininj dja daluk wanjh lawk bindiyilkbuni bindiborlidjmarnbuni.
(Andrew Manakgu, Injalak Arts painting documentation)
A man speared a buffalo, then took a knife and cut it up. He took the tongue and two ribs and carried them over his shoulder.

Ngardbakan nakka karohrok yiman karnubirr. Bu ngarridjare kuk ngarringun wanjh kunwardde ngarridong kabarrhme wanjh ngarringun
(Andrew Manakgu, Injalak Arts painting documentation)
yiman kayime
Bu kunwok Kunwinjku ngarriyime mayh ngarriwarlbun. Dja bu ngarriyime mayh ngarrire ngarribidbun karrkad wanjh nakka kore ceremony yiman Kunabibi mandjamun manbu bininj ngadberre.
(Andrew Manakgu, Injalak Arts painting documentation)
Saltwater mussels are similar to freshwater mussels. If we want to just eat them raw, we hit them with a rock, they split open and we can eat them like that.
similar to

In the Kunwinjku language, we say that we hunt mayh (animals). But when we say we’re going up to a mayh, in that case it means we’re going up to a ceremony, such as Kunabibi or another sacred event of ours.
Yimarnek ngarayi minj ngadjareniwirrinj.

Yimankek balhdungyibmi dja birribebmeng.

I should have gone but I didn't want to.
Then they tried to run away in fear but the Rainbow Serpent was watching them and she wrapped her tail around them.
It was just about sunset when they arrived.

Baleh karriyime?
Kunekke kayime.
Kamak, ngurrikan 'use' ngurriyime.
Njale kunwok ngundimarneyimeng?

What are we going to do?
That's the way it goes (it goes like that).
It's OK, you take it and use it.
What news did they tell you?

examples: Kaluk yekke kayimerran.

Wanjh nawu wurdyaw yimeng mamamh baleh kanyimowon.
(Andrew Manakgu, Injalak Arts painting documentation)

(Quoted in Etherington, Steve, ‘Learning to be Kunwinjku: Kunwinjku people discuss their pedagogy’, PhD Thesis, Charles Darwin University, 2006)
Manbu… manbolh wam kore Pine Creek, wanjh borledmi Darwin way. Kunih yimowoni manbolh kerrngehkenh bu.
(Quoted in Etherington, Steve, ‘Learning to be Kunwinjku: Kunwinjku people discuss their pedagogy’, PhD Thesis, Charles Darwin University, 2006)
How do I do this?

Let's go, I'll get diesel straight away.

translation: straight away, first, already, beforehand, in preparation

Kukyirrek.
Manbak kadjordme kuronj. Manyirrekyirrek.
Kabolhyirrek wardi karriyirdebme.

Kayirrek.
(Jill Nganjmirra)
Slippery body (i.e. an eel).

It's slimy/slippery.
Karnkurlkkuno, mandulum kayirriyo.
Wurdurd, ngurrikukmarnburrimen ngurriyirriyun!
Nawu Kune, Dangbon kayirriyo.
(The place we call) Karnkurlkkuno is a staight line of hills.
You kids organise yourself so you're all lying down next to each other (parallel).

translation: 1. lie, be (of long objects) 2. lie in parallel

In the old days, people would go into the forest searching [for honey], looking up at the trees. When they saw honey bees flying around they would chop down the tree and open it up, then they would get the fluid honey and pollen sacs and put them all together in a billy can.
Nawu nakurl ngarrinan koyekbeh kangolburlerran kawarnamkurrme, wanjh nakka kamre bu kundalk kakekurrme rowk, kore kurorre kayo.

Manme kayo?
A: Bukkanj kahni nakkanj? B: Kayo.
Yiyun!
Minj yuwirrinj.
Bedda benedjarrkyonginj.

We see late wet-season storms coming from the east, the clouds darken and make a dark horizontal bar on the horizon. It comes and knocks all the spear grass to the ground.
Is there any food?
A: Is he there that one [the one you should know I mean]? B: He's asleep.
Go to sleep!
S/he didn't sleep.

examples: "Yoh," yimeng ngalbininjkobeng.

Yowyowmeng rowk wanjh berlngdanj rowk wanjh birrimirrhkudjmey.

Birridokmeng yungki.

Djanay birrimbolkyurrhkeng birrimhdjalwam birriyonginj kore muddika kahdhjowkke.

Nani kabiyurrhke.
